The paper deals with two-player zero-sum games played on graphs, which are typically studied in the area of logic and automata theory (cs.LO). The focus is on parity games, which are a canonical way to encode omega-regular properties, and their variants with time bounds. This involves analyzing the complexity and memory bounds of various algorithms and approaches, which are common themes in computational game theory (cs.GT), algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper introduces a new type of game called window parity games, which is inspired by window mean-payoff games, a topic that falls under the area of computational complexity (cs.CC).
